Descriptive analysis of the posterior distributions (for the training set)

Decision on best models for description of past performance was based on direct estimates of AIC (Akaike, 1974) or its Monte Carlo approximation AICM (Raftery and Newton, 2007). Those are based on marginal likelihood estimation. Thus, the conditional likelihood should be estimated for each draw in the posterior sample.

## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess

The likelihood function for DV was defined by:

\(L_{DV} = \prod^{n}_{k=1}\pi_{ijk}^{I_{{y_{ijk}=1}}}\pi_{ijk0}^{I_{{y_{ijk}=0,5}}}\pi_{jik}^{I_{{y_{jik}=0}}}\)


where \(I_{()}\) represents indicator function for the results. We defined Y as matrix that stores all game results as follows:

Y          <- matrix(0,n,3)
Y[y==0,1]  <- 1 
Y[y==.5,2] <- 1
Y[y==1,3]  <- 1

Each result was compared to reference from each type of model using educated guesses (with naive estimation of probabilities). Basic assumptions for making those references were:

To assume summaries of historic results for wins, draws and losses from white players’ perspective. This ‘’proportional’’ model has probabilities actually estimated in original dataset and can be used to check DV.

propto    <- (table(y)/length(y))    # proportion of results, with draws


DVeropropto   <- sum(omegag*(Y[,1]*log(propto[1])+Y[,2]*log(propto[2])+Y[,3]*log(propto[3])))    # Log Likelihood

AICDavidpropW <- -2*DVeropropto +4       #AIc

To assume a win, a draw or a loss are equiprobable, meaning basic \(\frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3}\) and \(\frac{1}{3}\) to DV;

AICEqui <- -2*sum(omegag*(Y[,1]*log(1/3)+Y[,2]*log(1/3)+Y[,3]*log(1/3)))+4   # AIC for modelos with parameters Equiproblable

In this table is possible see the AIC value for reference models, (AICDavidpropW and AICEqui).

\[\begin{array}{cc} \hline \textrm{Reference model} &\textrm{ AIC} \\ \hline \textrm{Equiprobable} & 26610,4 \\ \textrm{Proportional} & 24129,0 \\ \hline \end{array}\]

We used R coda library for convergence diagnostics of the chains sampled from the posterior distribution.

#         Loading three generated chains for each parameter 
#           and the logarithm of the likelihood of the model.                     

c1DV1Wdg <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.gamaA.txt"))
c2DV1Wdg <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.gamaB.txt"))   # Three chains of rating (gama)
c3DV1Wdg <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.gamaC.txt"))
cadeiag <- mcmc.list(c1DV1Wdg,c2DV1Wdg,c3DV1Wdg)   # Concatenating the chains


c1DV1Wdd <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.deltaA.txt"))
c2DV1Wdd <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.deltaB.txt"))  # Three chains of advantage white (delta).
c3DV1Wdd <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.deltaC.txt"))
cadeiad <- mcmc.list(c1DV1Wdd,c2DV1Wdd,c3DV1Wdd)   # Concatenating the chains

c1DV1WE <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.lambdaA.txt"))
c2DV1WE <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.lambdaB.txt")) # Three chains of parameters Drawn (lambda).
c3DV1WE <- mcmc(read.table("cadeia.lambdaC.txt"))
cadeiaE <- mcmc.list(c1DV1WE,c2DV1WE,c3DV1WE)   # Concatenating the chains


l1DV1Wd <- read.table("cadeia.lVmA.txt")
l2DV1Wd <- read.table("cadeia.lVmB.txt")      # Three chains  the logarithm of the likelihood.
l3DV1Wd <- read.table("cadeia.lVmC.txt")
lVDV1Wdm.vec <- c(mean(l1DV1Wd$V1),mean(l2DV1Wd$V1),mean(l3DV1Wd$V1))

The diagnostic about convergence and independence of chain values, was done with function ( gelman.diag()) present library Coda of the R.

lVm1WdDV <- mean(lVDV1Wdm.vec)
varlVWmDV <- var(lVDV1Wdm.vec)

#-------------------# AICM for model 

AICM<--2*lVm1WdDV+2*varlVWmDV  # Log likelihook
\[\begin{array}{cc} \hline \textrm{Reference model} &\textrm{ AIC} \\ \hline \textrm{Equiprobable} & 26610,4 \\ \textrm{Proportional} & 24129,0 \\ \hline \textrm{Davidson Dynamic with $\delta$ } &21961,1 \\ \hline \end{array}\]

This model derived from Davidson basic version was better than respective reference models.

Plots of iterations vs. sampled values for variables in the chain and corresponding density plot. Trace of V1 is related \(\delta\) and Trace of V2 is related \(\lambda\).

plot(cadeiad)

plot(cadeiaE)

All models derived from Davidson basic version were better than respective reference models. Better models are fully parameterized, using both players white advantage parameters and a single drawing parameter, that was estimated as \(\lambda=1,098\) with \(HPD_{95\%}:~[1,04~;~1,15]\) for the static model and as \(\lambda=1,106\) with \(HPD_{95\%}:~[1,06~;~1,14]\) for the model with weighed likelihood.

Those estimates are indicative of a prevalent drawing tendency in games played at this level. Comparing these with rating estimates that one can find in figures, estimated by the best models (static and dynamic versions) is a good indicative of the extent those players are prone to draw.

To generate the graphs, the library “gplots” was used, through function barplot2.

Same procedure was carried to all other models. Code can be provided on demand.
